06407nam a2201165Ia 9781501725456DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20181996nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017254567 a10.7591/97815017254562doi  a(DE-B1597)515598  a(OCoLC)1129164293  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR428.R35bH35 1995 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a820.9/353220  aHI 11152rvk0(DE-625)rvk/49768:1 aHall, Kim F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThings of Darkness :bEconomies of Race and Gender in Early Modern England /cKim F. Hall. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b27 black-and white illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. A World of Difference: Travel Narratives and the Inscription of Culture -- t2. Fair Texts/Dark Ladies: Renaissance Lyric and the Poetics of Color -- t3. "Commerce and Intercourse": Dramas of Alliance and Trade -- t4. The Daughters of Eve and the Children of Ham: Race and the English Woman Writer -- t5. "An Object in the Midst of Other Objects": Race, Gender, Material Culture -- tEpilogue: On "Race," Black Feminism, and White Supremacy -- tAppendix: Poems of Blackness -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe "Ethiope," the "tawny Tartar," the "woman blackamoore," and "knotty Africanisms"—allusions to blackness abound in Renaissance texts. Kim F. Hall's eagerly awaited book is the first to view these evocations of blackness in the contexts of sexual politics, imperialism, and slavery in early modern England. Her work reveals the vital link between England's expansion into realms of difference and otherness—through exploration and colonialism-and the highly charged ideas of race and gender which emerged.How, Hall asks, did new connections between race and gender figure in Renaissance ideas about the proper roles of men and women? What effect did real racial and cultural difference have on the literary portrayal of blackness? And how did the interrelationship of tropes of race and gender contribute to a modern conception of individual identity? Hall mines a wealth of sources for answers to these questions: travel literature from Sir John Mandeville's Travels to Leo Africanus's History and Description of Africa; lyric poetry and plays, from Shakespeare's Antony and Cleopatra and The Tempest to Ben Jonson's Masque of Blackness; works by Emilia Lanyer, Philip Sidney, John Webster, and Lady Mary Wroth; and the visual and decorative arts.Concentrating on the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, Hall shows how race, sexuality, economics, and nationalism contributed to the formation of a modern (white, male) identity in English culture.The volume includes a useful appendix of not readily accessible Renaissance poems on blackness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBlack people in literature. 0aBlacks in literature. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aFeminism and literaturezEngland. 0aLiterature and societyzEngland. 0aRace in literature. 0aSex role in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aWomen and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aEngland. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aLiterary analysis.  aLiterary criticism.  aTheology.  aanxieties of race in literature.  ablackness in Renaissance texts.  ablacks in literature.  abooks on critical race theory.  abooks on race in Early Modern England.  ab